<TITLE> Ivory Coast police tear gas protesting students </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ABIDJAN, Sept 3 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Riot police in Ivory Coast's main city Abidjan fired tear gas on Monday to disperse students demanding compensation for damage by the security forces to their campus during a previous riot a year ago, witnesses said. Causing panic among local residents, the students blocked main roads and smashed car windows in several neighbourhoods of the lagoon-side city, one of two main ports through which the West African country's cocoa production is shipped. There was no immediate impact reported on the cocoa industry in the world's top grower. "The students started smashing vehicles in the streets this morning without warning and attacking people they came across," said Jacques Koue, a resident of the Port Bouet suburb who was trying to get to work. "We're looking for somewhere to shelter, both ourselves and our vehicles, because it's too dangerous," he said. The FESCI student movement which organised the protest has held similarly violent demonstrations in the past, often against French and other foreign interests in the former French colony. It is viewed as being close to the government of President Laurent Gbagbo and previous acts of violence have largely gone unpunished. Elections are due to be held early next year under a long-delayed peace plan aimed at reuniting the country, which was split into a rebel-held north and government-controlled south by a 2002/2003 civil w
